## Commit messages

Machine-parsed format (mr-creator depends on this shape):

```
[type]([scope]): [subject]

[optional body]

[optional footer]
```

Allowed `[type]` values: `feat | fix | docs | style | refactor | test | chore`

Examples:

- `feat(auth): add OAuth2 login`
- `fix(api): resolve timeout issue`
- `docs(readme): update setup instructions`

| Do                                       | Don't                              |
| ---------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------- |
| Keep each commit atomic                  | Mix unrelated changes in one commit |
| Write a descriptive, present-tense subject | Ship vague subjects ("fix stuff") |
| Reference the issue/ticket               | Use past tense                     |
| Give enough context in the body          | Leave the reason unstated          |

> Ticket references: the mr-creator skill enforces the ticket-ID format at commit time.
> Document the project's expected reference style in `[Details]`.

## Pull requests

PR title mirrors the commit format:

```
[type]([scope]): [description]
```

Description skeleton:

```markdown
## Summary
What and why, in a sentence or two.

## Changes
- Key change 1
- Key change 2

## Testing
How this was verified.

## Checklist
- [ ] Tests added or updated
- [ ] Manual verification done
- [ ] Complies with project standards
- [ ] All tests pass
- [ ] No merge conflicts
```

Reviewer checklist:

1. Standards compliance
2. Logic correctness
3. Test adequacy
4. Security
5. Docs updated

